'''''The Living Daylights''''' is a [[run and gun video game]] adaptation of the 1987 [[James Bond]] film ''[[The Living Daylights]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Andy Lane, Paul Simpson |title=The Bond Files: An Unofficial Guide to the World's Greatest Secret Agent|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vK0qJdsjgtcC|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|year=2002|ISBN=978-0-7535-0712-4 |page=408}}</ref> It was the second Bond game published by [[Domark]] following 1985's poorly received [[A View to a Kill (video game)#A View to a Kill: The Computer Game|''A View to a Kill: The Computer Game'']].<ref name='cvgbond'>{{cite magazine |title=The James Bond Dossier|magazine=Computer and Video Games|issue=68|publisher=EMAP|date=15 May 1987|page=78|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=1519&page=78|access-date=21 October 2022}}</ref>

The game was released for all major platforms at the time and developed by De Re Software (Atari 8-bit), Exasoft (BBC Micro), [[Sculptured Software]] (Commodore 64) and Walking Circles (Amstrad CPC/PCW, MSX, ZX Spectrum) from a design by Richard Naylor of Domark.<ref name='cvgbond'>{{cite magazine |title=The James Bond Dossier|magazine=Computer and Video Games|issue=68|publisher=EMAP|date=15 May 1987|page=78|url=https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=1519&page=78|access-date=21 October 2022}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The game was re-released as a [[light gun shooter]] on various [[cassette tape]]s with the [[ZX Spectrum]] 007 Action Pack. The plot was greatly rewritten, and explained on narration audiocassettes by [[Desmond Llewelyn]] as [[Q (James Bond)|Q]].<ref name="nostalgianerd20200719">{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u_-Nq497uA4 |title=That Time Amstrad Casually Rewrote James Bond | author=Nostalgia Nerd |date=2020-07-19 |language=en-GB |publisher=YouTube}}</ref>

